  boundaryHash (design together with fts_map incremental writes), CJK shingle
  search structure (#26 option a; interim = skip-row purge shipped in #96),
  MCP get_session first-request count-scan still O(file) (accepted tradeoff,
  cached after first request).

## 2026-07-03 - Full performance audit: 25 verified findings, roadmap only, nothing implemented (Claude)

- Ran a 49-agent workflow audit (wf_3946e4d0-4a4) across all runtime layers.
  43 raw findings -> 38 deduped -> 25 adversarially CONFIRMED (13 refuted with
  live measurements). ANALYSIS ONLY — no code changed. Full roadmap + findings
  JSON preserved at `~/.claude/projects/-Users-bing--Code--engram/2a2fe987-c55b-4676-8154-d23cf7ca992a/subagents/workflows/wf_3946e4d0-4a4/{roadmap.md,confirmed.json,refuted.json}`.
- Two structural root causes drive 12/25 findings:
  1. `readObjects` full-file JSON parse is the default whenever
     `StreamMessagesOptions.limit == nil` — indexer parses every changed file
     TWICE (`SwiftIndexer.scanSnapshots` parseSessionInfo + streamStats), MCP
     pager (`MCPTranscriptReader.swift:243`), resume primer, and legacy
     fallback all re-parse whole multi-MB transcripts per page.
  2. `sessions_fts.session_id` is UNINDEXED + one FTS row PER MESSAGE (256,292
     rows / 572MB of the 835MB DB) + delete-all/insert-all updates
     (`FTSRebuildPolicy.replaceFtsContent`) — every append to a live session
     full-scans the 460MB trigram index then re-tokenizes the entire
     transcript (one session re-indexed 6,480x per session_index_jobs).
- Top measured numbers (live 835MB / 29,093-session DB): local offline search
  fallback in `Database.swift:454-491` (correlated per-row FTS MATCH) takes
  80–100s vs 81ms for the service CTE (`EngramServiceReadProvider.keywordSearch`
  652–716) — port the CTE, effort S; startup FTS `optimize`
  (`StartupBackfills.swift:594`) costs ~7s holding the write gate on EVERY
  launch; CJK search LIKE full-scans 96MB per debounced keystroke (LIKE is
  deliberate — trigram MATCH unreliable for CJK, do NOT swap); 88% of sessions
  are tier=skip yet run the heavy second indexing pass whose output is
  discarded; `parsedOffset`/`boundaryHash` columns exist but are dead (no tail
  parsing). Recommended FTS fix: companion session_id->rowid map table +
  incremental inserts (avoids `FTSRebuildPolicy.expectedVersion` bump that
  would force full re-parse of all sessions).
- Notable REFUTED (don't re-flag): per-call SQLite connection opens (MCP ~18
  sites, export) measured negligible locally; FTS duplicate text storage
  (134MB) not worth changing; sessions-list page accumulation harmless;
  startup dedup GROUP BY scan cheap.

## 2026-06-28 - Project-detail vertical-rail timeline with AI semantic titles (Claude)

- Shipped a per-project work timeline in the Projects detail view (Workspace ->
  Projects -> select a project), under the project header via
  `ProjectWorkTimeline` (`macos/Engram/Components/ProjectWorkTimeline.swift`): a
  vertical rail (`TimelineRail`/`TimelineNode`) with color-coded
  `SessionImplementationKind` node dots; tapping a node opens the latest beat's
  session via the existing `.openSession`/`SessionBox` path. The global Timeline
  page keeps `WorkTimelineCard` (reverted to `private`).
- AI per-work-item semantic titles. New service-owned table `work_item_titles`
  (`project, work_key, title, intent_hash, model, updated_at`, PK(project,
  work_key)) added idempotently in `EngramMigrations.createOrUpdateBaseSchema`.
  IMPORTANT: deliberately NOT added to `SchemaManifest.baseTables` (would break
  the legacy UI-fixture SchemaCompatibilityTests, same precedent as
  `session_work_beats`).
- New IPC command `generateProjectWorkTitles` (full 6-layer wiring: protocol,
  client w/ `bulkAICommandTimeout`, mock, DTOs in EngramServiceModels, dispatch
  case, + `ServiceCapabilityToken.protectedCommands` allowlist — mutating
  commands MUST be listed there or they are rejected unauthorized). Handler:
  `readProjectWorkItems` (human-driven-filtered, mirrors
  `DatabaseManager.implementationTimeline`) -> per-item `intent_hash` = SHA256 of
  concatenated beats' humanIntent+assistantOutcome -> generate only missing/stale
  titles via `ServiceAISettings.titleConfig` (user's mimo) -> upsert. AI/network
  runs OUTSIDE `ServiceWriterGate`; only the upsert is inside it (generateSummary
  pattern). titleConfig nil => no-op, persists nothing (app keeps heuristic).
- App read: `ImplementationTimelineItem.semanticTitle` populated by a
  `tableExists("work_item_titles")`-guarded LEFT JOIN in
  `DatabaseManager.implementationTimeline` (project-scoped only; project=nil/
  global timeline must NOT pick up titles). UI prefers `semanticTitle ?? title`.
  On project open: heuristic shows instantly -> one on-demand generation pass
  (guarded by `requestedTitleGen` to prevent loops) -> in-place reload
  (`load(showSpinner:)` so the rail is not blanked/spinner-flashed).
- Testability seam: `generateProjectWorkTitles` takes injectable `titleConfig` +
  `generateTitle` params (production defaults read real settings / call the real
  model) so cache/no-op paths are deterministically testable without network.
- Robustness bug found by the new IPC test: a post-write re-SELECT of
  `work_item_titles` threw "no such table" on a non-migrated DB. Fixed by
  returning the generated titles directly (app ignores the response and reloads
  from DB anyway).
- Built via 2 ultracode workflows (parallel code-map/design -> 4 disjoint-file
  parallel implementers + build-fix loop + 3 adversarial reviewers). Committed in
  `e4164164`; full detail in CHANGELOG.md [Unreleased]. Verification: full Debug
  build + targeted Swift tests green (read-join x3, migration x14, service IPC/
  seam x3). Full suites/lint/packaging NOT run.
- Codex review follow-up on 2026-06-28 found no behavior blocker in the Claude
  implementation. It cleaned the newly added Swift comments/prompt text to match
  the repo's English/ASCII source-comment convention and verified `xcodegen
  generate` is stable plus the focused app read-join tests (3), service
  generateProjectWorkTitles tests (3), migration schema test (1), and
  `git diff --check`.
- Ready-for-review subagent pass before merging PR #93 found one real blocker:
  empty/whitespace AI work-item titles could be persisted with the current
  `intent_hash`, causing later generation passes to treat the item as cached
  while the app ignored the empty semantic title and kept showing the heuristic.
  Fixed by trimming generated titles and skipping empty results before upsert;
  added `testGenerateProjectWorkTitlesSkipsEmptyTitlesSoTheyCanRetry` to prove
  the empty attempt persists nothing and retries successfully.

