## 2026-06-20 - Plain-HTTP-over-Tailscale offload + second server macmini-hq live

- Objective: install remote offload onto a NEW host `ssh bing@10.0.10.100`
  (= tailnet `macmini-hq`, Tailscale IP `100.125.101.60`, MagicDNS
  `macmini-hq.tail1cb16.ts.net`, macOS 26.5.1, Swift 6.3) and run a real
  offload→rehydrate while monitoring. Distinct host from the prior `macmini-m1`
  (`100.108.19.20`). See [[2026-06-20 - Remote offload server deployed to macmini-m1]].
- DESIGN CHANGE (owner-driven): forcing HTTPS certs on a Tailscale/LAN transport
  is overkill — WireGuard already encrypts+authenticates. `EngramRemoteBackend`
  now takes `requireTLS` (primitive default true; product reads new setting
  `remoteOffloadRequireTLS`, default OFF). Permissive mode allows plain HTTP to
  loopback + private/CGNAT(`100.64/10`=Tailscale)/`.ts.net`/`.local`/bare-LAN
  hosts; PUBLIC hosts still require TLS in BOTH modes (token-leak guard). Test
  `testRemoteBackendTLSPolicy`, suite 7/7. → no nginx/Homebrew/private-CA needed.
- Server: built `EngramRemoteServer` on dev Mac (Debug, CODE_SIGNING_ALLOWED=NO),
  relocatable bundle (binary + `EngramRemoteServerCore.framework`, ad-hoc signed;
  `libswiftCompatibilitySpan.dylib` is a symlink→libswiftCore on macOS 26, not
  bundled — keygen ran on target = runtime deps OK). Shipped to
  `~/.engram-remote`, env `ENGRAM_REMOTE_HOST=100.125.101.60` (binds Tailscale
  iface, not 0.0.0.0/LAN) plain HTTP :8787, launchd `com.engram.remote-server`
  KeepAlive. Token reused from Keychain; fresh at-rest key via `keygen`.
- Pre-deploy drain (audit-mandated): the live DB had 5 sessions
  `offload_state='offloaded'` (ids cc13d478, 9c45c4b7, 191ae4eb, a859a8fc,
  c19e3657) with bundles only on the OLD server. CRITICAL: repointing to an empty
  new server strands them (404 rehydrate is terminal, reindex refuses while
  offloaded, no repair cmd).
- INCIDENT: draining to local didn't stick because the still-running OLD
  background loop (built once at startup, fixed config, fires ~5 min) re-offloaded
  them to the OLD server during the deploy window. LESSON: STOP/freeze the offload
  loop before repointing or draining. Fixed deterministically by a server→server
  bundle copy (`GET old` decrypted plaintext → `PUT new` re-encrypted with the new
  at-rest key, same content-addressed keys) — no DB/loop race. All 5 now on new.
- Verified e2e against the NEW server: IPC rehydrate restored full FTS (sessions_fts
  321 B shadow → 13 456 B), `offload_state`→local; re-offload settled offloaded=5;
  invariant "every offloaded session has a bundle on new server" = 0 misses; raw
  transcripts untouched. Old server (`100.108.19.20`) left running as a backup copy.
- OPS TOOLING: drove drain/offload/rehydrate/status via a tiny framed-JSON unix
  socket client (`/tmp/engram_ipc.py`): 4-byte BE length + envelope
  `{request_id,kind:"request",command,payload:base64,capability_token}` read from
  `~/.engram/run/cmd.token`; commands `remoteSyncStatus` (no token),
  `remoteOffload`/`remoteRehydrate {sessionId}` (token). NOTE: the login shell is
  zsh — it does NOT word-split unquoted `$var`; iterate ids with arrays or
  `while read`, not `for x in $list`.
- Open hardening (audit `wf0fworum`, non-blocking): server returns 201 on a
  non-fsynced `.atomic` write (BlobStore.put); no client read-back verify after
  PUT before purge; no operator repair command for stranded sessions; an offloaded
  session that later gains content silently drops appends.

## 2026-06-20 - Remote offload server deployed to macmini-m1

- Objective: deploy + test the self-hosted `EngramRemoteServer` (the offload
  backend) on the remote host `macmini-m1` (`ssh bing@macmini-m1`).
- Remote env: Apple Silicon, macOS 26.6, **Command-Line-Tools only (no Xcode →
  no remote `xcodebuild`)**, but has Swift 6.4 toolchain + git + rsync. Repo
  also present at remote `~/engram` (different from local `~/-Code-/engram`).
  Pre-existing LaunchAgent `com.engram.dashscope-proxy` (so the host runs user
  agents; implies GUI auto-login).
- Build/test (local, Debug): `EngramRemoteServerCoreTests` 6/6; HTTP smoke of
  the shippable bundle 13/13; app-side `RemoteSyncCoordinatorTests`+
  `RemoteSyncIPCTests` 5/5; `RemoteOffloadTests`+`MigrationRunnerTests` 19/19.
- KEY DEPLOY FACT: `EngramRemoteServerCore.framework` **statically links
  Hummingbird/NIO** (Build/Products has only `.o`, no Hummingbird dylib). So the
  relocatable bundle is just `bin/EngramRemoteServer` +
  `Frameworks/EngramRemoteServerCore.framework` +
  `Frameworks/libswiftCompatibilitySpan.dylib`. Both binary and framework
  already carry rpaths `@executable_path/../Frameworks` and `/usr/lib/swift`, so
  it relocates with NO `install_name_tool` surgery — only an ad-hoc re-sign
  (`codesign --force -s -`) after assembly so arm64 will exec it. The compat
  span dylib also exists in the OS `/usr/lib/swift`, so it's belt-and-suspenders.
- Deploy layout on remote (`~/.engram-remote/`): `bin/`, `Frameworks/`, `store/`
  (0700), `env` (0600, holds `ENGRAM_REMOTE_TOKEN`=32B hex +
  `ENGRAM_REMOTE_AT_REST_KEY`=32B base64 server-held + STORE/HOST/PORT),
  `run.sh` (0700 wrapper: `set -a; . env; set +a; exec bin/EngramRemoteServer`).
  LaunchAgent `~/Library/LaunchAgents/com.engram.remote-server.plist`
  (RunAtLoad+KeepAlive, Background) runs `run.sh`. Secrets are NEVER in the
  plist or argv — only in the 0600 env file. Logs: `~/.engram-remote/{stdout,
  stderr}.log`.
- App server bound **127.0.0.1:8787** (loopback only; behind the TLS proxy).
  Loaded via `launchctl bootstrap gui/$(id -u) <plist>`.
- Verified on remote: end-to-end 8/8 (health 200, no-auth PUT 401, auth
  PUT/HEAD/GET/DELETE lifecycle, at-rest ciphertext); KeepAlive respawn
  (kill pid → new pid + health 200); startup log
  `engram-remote listening on 127.0.0.1:8787`.
- LAN EXPOSURE (best practice, added same day): the app server is plain-HTTP by
  design and the client refuses non-HTTPS non-loopback URLs, so LAN exposure is
  via **nginx TLS reverse proxy**, NOT by binding the app server to the LAN.
  macmini already runs homebrew nginx 1.31.2 (`--with-http_ssl_module`) via
  `brew services`, with `include servers/*.conf`. Added
  `/opt/homebrew/etc/nginx/servers/engram-remote.conf` (alongside untouched
  campus/dingtalk vhosts): TLS on `*:8443`, `proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8787`
  for `/v1/`, forwards `Authorization` (app server still does the bearer check),
  `client_max_body_size 96m` (MUST exceed 64 MiB `maxBundleBytes`; nginx default
  1m would 413), TLSv1.2/1.3. Private CA at `~/.engram-remote/tls/` (`ca.key`
  4096 0600); server cert CA-signed, 825d, EKU serverAuth, SAN = `Bing-M1-
  MacMini.local, macmini-m1, localhost, 10.0.8.9, 127.0.0.1`. Reload with
  `nginx -t && nginx -s reload`. LAN IP 10.0.8.9.
- Verified from a LAN peer (the dev Mac): `https://10.0.8.9:8443` +
  `https://Bing-M1-MacMini.local:8443` health 200 against the CA; no-CA
  connection REJECTED (real TLS, not `-k`); no-token → 401 through proxy; authed
  PUT/HEAD/GET/DELETE + 3 MB bundle round-trip pass; 8787 still 127.0.0.1-only.
- CLIENT TRUST (needs admin, per client): `EngramRemoteBackend` uses
  `URLSession.shared` with NO custom delegate → standard TLS validation, no
  pinning, no insecure escape hatch (only loopback is exempt). So each client
  Mac must trust the CA once:
  `sudo security add-trusted-cert -d -r trustRoot -k
  /Library/Keychains/System.keychain <ca.crt>` (CA copied to
  `/tmp/engram-remote-ca.crt` on the dev Mac).
- LIVE offload→rehydrate VERIFIED (2026-06-20) against the deployed server via
  `RemoteSyncCoordinatorTests.testLiveOffloadRehydrateAgainstDeployedServer` (a
  gated sibling of the local-backend test; only diff = `EngramRemoteBackend`
  instead of `LocalDirectoryBackend`; skips without `ENGRAM_LIVE_OFFLOAD_URL/_TOKEN`
  env or `~/.engram-live-offload.json`). PASS: seeded session bundled +
  AES-GCM-encrypted + PUT (macmini store 0→1, 513 B ciphertext); `offload_state`→
  `offloaded` with only the keyword shadow; rehydrate GET restored `local` +
  full FTS content byte-for-byte. Test bundle deleted after (store back to 0).
- TWO CLIENT-REACHABILITY GOTCHAS (the client uses `URLSession` w/ no delegate →
  standard validation; only loopback is exempt from the https guard):
  1. macOS **Local Network Privacy** blocks a process from LAN private IPs until
     granted — the xctest harness got `-1009 "Local network prohibited"` on
     `10.0.8.9`. The shipping app triggers the "find devices on your local
     network" consent on first LAN offload; must be granted.
  2. mDNS `.local` does NOT resolve for URLSession under the active TUN/VPN
     (Surge-style `198.18.0.1`): `Bing-M1-MacMini.local` → `-1009`, IP worked.
     Prefer the IP / a real DNS name for `remoteOffloadServerURL`.
  - Workaround that made the test pass: SSH loopback tunnel
    `ssh -L 8788:127.0.0.1:8443 bing@macmini-m1` → `https://127.0.0.1:8788`
    (loopback bypasses Local Network Privacy; cert SAN has 127.0.0.1 so TLS still
    validates). Also a valid client transport when Local Network can't be granted.
    NOTE: with the TUN up, the SSH ControlMaster (`-M`) to `macmini-m1` is flaky
    ("port 22: Undefined error: 0"); use a plain `ssh -N -L` and curl-verify the
    forward (health 200) before relying on it.
- DONE (2026-06-20): the REAL `Engram.app` now auto-offloads over Tailscale.
  Config in `~/.engram/settings.json`: `remoteOffloadEnabled:true`,
  `remoteOffloadBackend:"http"`, `remoteOffloadServerURL:"https://100.108.19.20:8443"`
  (macmini TAILSCALE IP), `remoteOffloadColdAgeDays:365`. Token in Keychain via
  `security add-generic-password -A -s com.engram.remote-offload -a default -w <tok>`
  (the `-A` makes it readable by the helper without an ACL prompt). `remoteSyncStatus`
  IPC confirmed `enabled:true` + counts. Ran a real cycle: 5 cold (28 MB, >1 yr)
  sessions offloaded (macmini store 0→5, each left with 1 keyword shadow), 1
  rehydrated back to full FTS via `remoteRehydrate` IPC. Backup of settings at
  `~/.engram/settings.json.bak.*`.
- CRITICAL DEPLOY LESSON — use a TAILSCALE IP, NOT the LAN IP. Offload runs in the
  `EngramService` HELPER (separate process, designated id `EngramService`), and
  macOS **Local Network Privacy** prohibits the helper from the LAN subnet
  (`10.0.8.9` → every PUT `-1009 "Local network prohibited"`; the app's only TCC
  grant is Full-Disk-Access, and a background helper can't get a Local Network
  consent prompt). **Tailscale IPs route over `utun`, are NOT the local subnet, so
  they bypass Local Network Privacy** — switching the URL to the tailnet IP made
  every PUT succeed. Required re-issuing the nginx server cert with the tailscale
  IP added to the SAN (`IP:100.108.19.20`); the cert now covers LAN + tailscale +
  loopback, nginx still listens `*:8443`.
- Eligibility/candidate-window gotcha: `OffloadRepo.candidateRows` =
  `WHERE offload_state='local' ORDER BY size_bytes DESC LIMIT 500`, THEN
  `OffloadPolicy.isEligible`. So offload prioritizes the 500 LARGEST sessions; a
  "hidden-only" run is a no-op if the hidden sessions are smaller than the
  500th-largest (they were here). Lowering `coldAgeDays` brings large cold sessions
  into range. The runner builds the auto-loop coordinator ONCE at startup, but the
  IPC `remoteOffload`/`remoteSyncStatus` handlers rebuild it per-call from current
  settings — so settings changes need a service restart for the AUTO-loop, but take
  effect immediately for IPC-triggered cycles.
- Manual IPC driver (uncommitted): `/tmp/engram_ipc.py` — 4-byte BE length + JSON
  envelope `{request_id,kind:"request",command,payload(base64 Data),capability_token}`;
  token at `~/.engram/run/cmd.token` (0600); response payload is the base64 field
  `result`; commands `remoteOffload`/`remoteRehydrate`(payload `{"sessionId":...}`)/
  `remoteSyncStatus`/`recordSessionAccess`.
- Caveats: GUI LaunchAgent only runs while logged in (a LaunchDaemon needs
  sudo for login-independent start). Deployed the Debug artifact (the one that
  passed smoke); a Release rebuild can swap in later. To rotate the at-rest key
  later: existing stored blobs become undecryptable (server-held key), so only
  rotate against an empty/rehydrated store.

## 2026-06-20 - Remote session offload feature shipped (PR #87)

- Objective: offload cold/archived sessions' regenerable index artifacts to a
  self-hosted server to reclaim local disk/CPU. Designed + implemented across 8
  phases via multi-agent workflows, then hardened by a 6-dimension adversarial
  review.
- Status: MERGED to main as `5fcac98c` (PR #87 squash-merged 2026-06-20; branch
  deleted). Release-built + deployed to `/Applications/Engram.app` and running.
  Opt-in, default OFF — NOT active until `remoteOffloadEnabled: true` in
  `~/.engram/settings.json` + a backend configured (no sessions move otherwise).
- What ships:
  - Only regenerable artifacts (`sessions_fts` content + summary) are offloaded;
    raw transcript bytes on disk are NEVER moved. Offloaded sessions keep one
    keyword "shadow" FTS line so they stay searchable; `VACUUM` returns disk to
    the OS (`checkpointTruncate` is WAL-only, so deletes alone do not shrink).
  - Self-hosted `engram-remote`: standalone Hummingbird target, bearer auth +
    AES-GCM at-rest (server-held key), NEVER bundled in `Engram.app`. Client
    `EngramRemoteBackend` (URLSession) refuses non-HTTPS non-loopback URLs.
  - `RemoteSyncCoordinator` driven from `runIndexingLoop`; IPC commands
    `remoteOffload`/`remoteRehydrate`/`remoteSyncStatus` (capability-token gated);
    read-path lazy rehydrate via `recordSessionAccess`.
- Owner-locked decisions: self-hosted server backend; server-held key (NOT
  zero-knowledge); no remote analysis in v1; eligibility includes visible-but-
  cold sessions (requires the keyword shadow so they stay discoverable).
- Invariants in code: single SQLite writer via `ServiceWriterGate` (network runs
  OUTSIDE the gate; FTS purge only after a confirmed remote PUT); the re-index
  guard in `IndexJobRunner` covers BOTH periodic re-index AND full FTS rebuild;
  offload commit uses an optimistic `sync_version` guard (abort + re-queue if
  re-indexed mid-flight).
- Adversarial review (per-finding verified against code): fixed a critical
  content race, stuck-`inflight` recovery + retry-until-cap, `sync_ledger`
  ON DELETE CASCADE, HEAD invalid-key 400, fixed-length-digest token compare.
  AES-GCM nonce handling, env-only server secrets, and Keychain accessibility
  were confirmed correct.
- Tests: `EngramServiceCoreTests` (215), `EngramCoreTests` RemoteOffload/Migration/
  IndexerParity, `EngramRemoteServerCoreTests`, and full CI (incl. ui-test-full) green.
  CI LESSONS (the local subset missed these): (1) the indexer-parity test now
  EXCLUDES the Swift-only `offload_state` column vs the Node golden; (2)
  `test-fixtures/test-index.sqlite` is `npm run generate:fixtures`-deterministic —
  do NOT hand-edit it (the app migrates the DB at runtime, so read paths get
  `offload_state` without baking it into the fixture).
- Known follow-ups (not blockers): in-process TLS (currently via reverse proxy),
  Linux server build (CryptoKit -> swift-crypto + SPM), App UI to surface
  offloaded state / manual trigger; full `EngramCoreTests` (447) not run locally.
- Resume next session: feature is merged + live. To exercise it end-to-end:
  `EngramRemoteServer keygen` for the at-rest key, start the server with
  `ENGRAM_REMOTE_TOKEN` + `ENGRAM_REMOTE_AT_REST_KEY` + `ENGRAM_REMOTE_STORE`, then
  set `remoteOffloadEnabled` / `remoteOffloadBackend:"http"` / `remoteOffloadServerURL`
  in settings + store the token via `RemoteCredentialStore`. Deploy build used plain
  `xcodebuild` (CFBundleVersion=1, not the build-release.sh timestamp).
- Detail: `CHANGELOG.md` [Unreleased].

## 2026-06-19 - Codex fixed menu/live-session polling load and redeployed

- Objective: investigate whether Engram was contributing to local sluggishness,
  then implement and ship the performance fixes with TDD, review, and local
  deploy.
- Root causes found:
  - `FileSystemEngramServiceReadProvider.liveSessions()` materialized full
    recursive session roots on every menu cadence before applying the 100-result
    cap.
  - `AppDelegate` started a second service status/events stream while
    `EngramServiceLauncher.startHealthMonitor()` already ran the periodic
    status probe and stdout event sink.
  - `ServiceWriterGate.indexStatus()` did two status COUNT reads per health
    request; this was smaller than live-session scanning but still worth a short
    cache.
- Changes:
  - `macos/EngramService/Core/EngramServiceReadProvider.swift`: live sessions
    now stream enumerator candidates, keep only newest 100 candidates, parse
    metadata only for selected candidates, and reuse a 30s live-session cache.
  - `macos/Engram/App.swift`: removed the legacy `serviceClient.events()`
    status/event pump; service events now flow through the launcher stdout sink
    and status polling through the single health monitor.
  - `macos/EngramService/Core/ServiceWriterGate.swift`: added a 10s
    generation-aware `indexStatus()` cache that is cleared on write start,
    bypassed while writes are in flight, and invalidated on successful or failed
    gated writes.
  - Added regression coverage in `EngramServiceIPCTests`,
    `ServiceWriterGateTests`, `ViewMainThreadReadTests`, and
    `ServiceEventRoutingTests`.
- Review: an independent read-only reviewer found one Medium issue in the first
  cache implementation: actor reentrancy could return stale cached status while
  a write was suspended. Fixed by clearing/bypassing cache during in-flight
  writes and adding tests for in-flight writes plus mutate-then-throw failures.
- Verification:
  - Targeted live-session RED/GREEN tests passed after implementation.
  - Targeted duplicate status/event poll tests passed after removing the
    legacy AppDelegate pump.
  - Targeted index-status cache tests passed, including in-flight write and
    mutate-then-throw coverage.
  - Full `EngramServiceCore` scheme passed:
    `rtk xcodebuild test -project macos/Engram.xcodeproj -scheme EngramServiceCore -destination 'platform=macOS' CODE_SIGNING_ALLOWED=NO`.
  - App/Core unit targets passed:
    `rtk xcodebuild test -project macos/Engram.xcodeproj -scheme Engram -destination 'platform=macOS' CODE_SIGNING_ALLOWED=NO -only-testing:EngramTests -only-testing:EngramCoreTests`.
  - Full `Engram` scheme was attempted but `EngramUITests-Runner` hung before
    establishing the test-runner connection after 419s; no product assertion
    failure was emitted.
- Deploy:
  - Built with
    `ENGRAM_BUILD_NUMBER=20260619100353 macos/scripts/build-release.sh --local-only`.
    Developer ID export succeeded at `macos/build/EngramExport/Engram.app`;
    `release-verify` passed full Developer ID checks.
  - Installed with
    `macos/scripts/deploy-local.sh macos/build/EngramExport/Engram.app`,
    replacing `/Applications/Engram.app`.
  - Live smoke: `/Applications/Engram.app` reports
    `CFBundleVersion=20260619100353`; `codesign --verify --deep --strict
    --verbose=2 /Applications/Engram.app` passed. `Engram` PID 19252 and
    `EngramService` PID 19255 started from `/Applications/Engram.app`.
    Startup CPU briefly reached indexing load, then after 60s both Engram and
    EngramService sampled at 0.0% CPU. `mcp__engram.stats` returned today's
    source counts, proving the installed MCP/service path stayed usable.
- Residual risk:
  - EngramUITests runner connection hang remains unproven/environmental; rerun
    UI tests separately before treating the full UI suite as green.
  - Several long-running `EngramMCP` helper processes existed before deploy and
    remained at 0.0% CPU; they were not killed because they may belong to active
    MCP client sessions.

## 2026-06-15 — GRDB must be the single dynamic `GRDB-dynamic` product (runtime crash fix)

- **Hard rule:** every Xcode target links GRDB via the SPM **`GRDB-dynamic`**
  product (a single shared dynamic framework), NOT the static `GRDB` product.
  Do not switch back to `product: GRDB` — it regresses the crash below.
- **Why:** the `EngramService` helper process loads three dynamic frameworks
  (`EngramCoreRead` → `EngramCoreWrite` → `EngramServiceCore`). With the static
  `GRDB` product, each one statically embeds a full GRDB copy (~6450 symbols,
  `SchedulingWatchdog` ×9), so the process held THREE copies / three thread-local
  watchdog registries. A DB cursor created under one copy and iterated via
  another tripped a false `SchedulingWatchdog.preconditionValidQueue` SIGTRAP —
  "Database was not used on the correct thread" from `SQLStatementCursor.next()` —
  and `EngramService` crash-looped at runtime. Same triple-embed = the objc
  "class implemented in both" warnings and the host-only crash that BLOCKED
  DB-backed unit tests locally. (GRDB's own docs: pick `GRDB-dynamic` when
  linking GRDB into multiple targets in one process.)
- **Bundling:** `macos/scripts/copy-service-helper.sh` copies
  `GRDB-dynamic.framework` into `Engram.app/Contents/Frameworks` so the helper +
  app load the one shared copy via `@rpath/../Frameworks`. The SPM dynamic
  product is emitted under `PackageFrameworks/` for plain `xcodebuild build` and
  directly in `BUILT_PRODUCTS_DIR` for `archive` — the script checks BOTH.
  `EngramMCP`/`EngramCoreSchemaTool` got `LD_RUNPATH_SEARCH_PATHS` entries.
- **Side effect (good):** the host-local "GRDB duplicate-linkage thread crash"
  is GONE — DB-backed `EngramServiceCoreTests` now run locally (177/177).
- **UI tests:** Observability is gated behind `@AppStorage("showDeveloperTools")`
  (default OFF; `SidebarView` filters it out). UI tests reach it by launching
  with `-showDeveloperTools YES` (NSUserDefaults argument domain, same mechanism
  as `-AppleLanguages` in `TestLaunchConfig`). Heavy diagnostics views
  (LogStreamView) need a generous container wait (15s, not 5s) in the nav smoke.
- **Shipped on `main`:** PR #74 (UX flow alignment, 20 WP) + #75 (GRDB-dynamic) +
  #76 (de-flake jsonl-patch CAS test) + #77 (npm audit fix). Redeployed
  `/Applications/Engram.app` build `20260615195924`; service stable, zero new
  crash reports over the smoke window; MCP reads (stats/costs) functional.

